edu.mit.jwi
Class Dictionary

java.lang.Object
  edu.mit.jwi.Dictionary
All Implemented Interfaces:
IDataSourceDictionary, IDictionary, IHasVersion
public class Dictionary
extends java.lang.Object
implements IDataSourceDictionary

Basic implementation of the IDictionary interface. A path to the Wordnet dictionary files must be provided. If no IDataProvider is specified, it uses the default implementation provided with the distribution.

This dictionary caches items it retrieves. The cache is limited in size by default. See ItemCache.DEFAULT_MAXIMUM_CAPACITY. If you find this default maximum size does suit your purposes, you can retrieve the cache via the getCache() method and set the maximum cache size via the ItemCache.setMaximumCapacity(int) method. If you have a specialized implementation for your cache, you can subclass the Dictionary class and override the createCache() method.

Since:
1.5.0 (Nov. 16, 2007)

getIndexWord

public IIndexWord getIndexWord(IIndexWordID id)
Description copied from interface: IDictionary
Fetches the specified index word object from the database. If the specified lemma/pos combination is not found, returns null. Note: This call does no stemming on the specified lemma, it is taken as specified. That is, if you submit the word "dogs", it will search for "dogs", not "dog", and find nothing. This is in contrast to the Wordnet API provided by Princeton. If you want your searches to capture morphological variation, using the descendants of the IStemmer class.

Specified by:
getIndexWord in interface IDictionary

setHeadWord

protected void setHeadWord(ISynset synset)
This method sets the head word on the specified synset by searching in the dictionary to find the head of its cluster. We will assume the head is the first adjective head synset related by an '&' pointer (SIMILAR_TO) to this synset.
